@page "/getting-started/themes"

<PageTitle>Themes - Tavenem Blazor Framework</PageTitle>

<h1>Themes</h1>

<p>
	This page explains how you can customize the style and appearance of your
	Tavenem Blazor Framework app.
</p>

<h2>CSS Custom Properties</h2>

<p>
    The Tavenem Blazor Framework uses an extensive set of <a
    href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/--*">CSS custom
    properties</a> (a.k.a. CSS variables) to allow for easy customization of the
    included colors and styles.
</p>
<p>
	You can easily customize the look of your app by assigning new values to
	these properties in your own app's CSS. They are all set on the
	<code>:root</code> CSS pseudo-class.
</p>
<p>
	Make sure to include your own CSS file after the framework's CSS in your
	<code>index.html</code> (Blazor WebAssembly) or <code>_Host.cshtml</code>
	(Blazor Server).
</p>
<p>
	See <NavLink href="#list">below</NavLink> for the list of properties,
	along with default values and descriptions.
</p>

<h2>Light and Dark Mode</h2>

<p>
	The Tavenem Blazor Framework has built-in support for light and dark mode. See <a
	href="./components/lightdarktoggle">dark mode toggle</a> for details.
</p>
<p>
	Every property which starts with "--tavenem-light" or "--tavenem-dark" also
	has a corresponding property which starts with just "--tavenem". That
	property will automatically fetch the light or dark variant, depending on
	whether your app is currently in light or dark mode.
</p>
<p>
	For example: <code>--tavenem-color-text</code> will evaluate to either
	<code>var(--tavenem-light-color-text)</code> or <code>var(--tavenem-dark-color-text)</code>,
	depending on the current mode.
</p>
<p>
	These properties allow you to customize the look of your app in light and
	dark mode.
</p>

<h2>Theme Colors</h2>
<p>
	The Tavenem Blazor Framework has a color palette with @(Enum.GetValues<ThemeColor>().Length - 1) basic colors:
</p>
<div class="row fill my-3">
	@foreach (var color in Enum.GetValues<ThemeColor>().Where(x => x != ThemeColor.None))
	{
		<div class="@($"d-flex flex-column rounded filled {color.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()}")" style="min-width: 12em">
			<p class="py-5 mb-0 text-center">@color.ToString()</p>
			<div class="d-flex rounded-bottom">
				<div class="@($"flex-grow-1 filled lighten rounded-bottom-left {color.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()}")">
					<p class="py-3 mb-0 text-center">Lighten</p>
				</div>
				<div class="@($"flex-grow-1 filled darken rounded-bottom-right {color.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()}")">
					<p class="py-3 mb-0 text-center">Darken</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	}
</div>
<p>
	The theme colors are defined with hue, saturation, and lightness values so that lighter, darker,
	and transparent versions can be generated automatically via derived properties, without
	requiring separate properties or recompilation of the source.
</p>
<p>
	There are light and dark mode variations of each theme color's hue, saturation, and lightness,
	as well as the color of text which will show up best against a background of that color. Each
	color has been selected to meet WCAG 2.0 level AA contrast guidelines when set against the
	default background color for its color scheme, or when used as a background color with text of
	the default color.
</p>
<p>
	Each theme color has two lighter and darker varieties, which can change the lightness value by
	up to 20%. As a result, you should ensure that the lightness values you select for your theme
	colors are no less than 20 and no greater than 80. Ideally they should be well away from either
	extreme, since a lightness value too close to 0 will be indistunguishable from black, and a
	value too close to 100 will be indistinguishable from white.
</p>
<p>
	Each theme and its variations exist as utility classes which can be used to control the color of
	most elements. The theme color by itself, used as a class, sets the foreground color to that
	theme color (and the border color, although it does not actually add a border). You can add the
	<code>lighten</code> or <code>darken</code> class to modify the lightness.
</p>
<p>
	Please note that the lightened and darkened version of the theme colors may not meet WCAG 2.0
	level AA contrast guidelines when used as text colors, or when used as background colors with
	text of the default color. Use them with caution.
</p>
<p>
	If you add the <code>filled</code> class, the background color is set to the theme color, and
	the foreground to an appropriate contrasting text color (as seen in the swatches above). You can
	also use the <code>border-{theme}</code> classes to set the border color to a theme color.
</p>
<p>
	The theme classes are:
</p>
<ul>
	@foreach (var color in Enum.GetValues<ThemeColor>().Where(x => x != ThemeColor.None))
	{
		<li><code>@color.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()</code></li>
	}
</ul>
<p>
	You may note that unlike some other style frameworks, the "success" theme color is a shade of
	blue, rather than green. This choice was made to provide better support for colorblind users,
	for whom the contrast between a red "danger" (often used to indicate a failure or error state),
	and a green "success" may be difficult to determine. Green is used instead for the "info" theme
	color, as it is generally less critical to visually distinguish "info" and "danger" states.
</p>

